@divergence The canonical pattern deepens this via whole-board play
(backward propagation reaching the outermost level as meta-learning)
and Sen (feedback as conversion factor for persistence).  The paper
frames it as Ostrom's monitoring problem — the monitoring chain has
too many links for the current governance structure to sustain.  The
paper's resolution is concrete: cross-institutional peer evaluation
with a lightweight instrument, where trainers interview each other's
recipients.  This variant records the paper's framing.

! conclusion: The programme needs evidence of downstream impact to improve, sustain trainer motivation, and justify institutional support, but current feedback mechanisms are thin.  The resolution is to distribute monitoring across the actors it serves — cross-institutional peer evaluation where trainers interview each other's recipients using a lightweight instrument.  This is Ostrom's monitoring problem: the current evaluation chain has too many links for the existing governance structure to sustain, so the governance structure itself must adapt via a reciprocal network.
  + context: This is NPT Reflexive Monitoring — specifically 4.2 Communal Appraisal: shared mechanisms for evaluating what is working and what is not.  It is an architecture-tier pattern with very high coordination — a multi-actor evaluation chain, the highest coordination requirement under the current design.  The paper notes this is the *only* pattern where quantitative COM-B data and qualitative transcript analysis produce a convergent signal independently arriving at the same conclusion.  Its failure is the central impediment to multiplied input at network scale; only fully resolved, it converts absorbed/mismatch dynamics into programme-level learning.
  + IF:
    A distributed training programme has resolved (or is resolving) Patterns 1-4: trainers have expectations, provisioning, stewarded materials, and pathways into governance.  Local and community-level learning operate.  But the programme cannot see its own aggregate effects across institutions, cohorts, and time.  Its funders, its institutional leads, and its trainers all need evidence that the effort produces downstream impact — evidence the current feedback mechanisms cannot produce.
  + HOWEVER:
    Feedback mechanisms are thin.  Trainers rely on optional post-session surveys that yield only positive responses or none at all (T2B: "I have no other ways of getting feedback short of people filling in the feedback form"; T2B: "As we get like a few answers and nobody says this was terrible, I generally think it's gone quite well").  Informal signals from colleagues are all that is available (FG2B.41, FG2B.36, FG2B.39).  COM-B: "effects are being measured" M=3.35 — the lowest item across all survey waves, dropping to M=3.17 at 6-month follow-up.  Cross-institutional analysis is absent.  An evaluation workstream was funded but the evaluation chain — from instrument design through data collection to cross-institutional analysis to feedback back to trainers — was not built.  This is the monitoring chain with too many links for the current governance structure to sustain.
  + THEN:
    The programme develops and deploys cross-institutional peer evaluation: trainers interview each other's recipients using a lightweight instrument.  Monitoring is distributed across the actors it serves — a reciprocal network.  The evaluation chain is designed end-to-end before the next delivery event, with named roles at each link (instrument, collection, cross-institutional analysis, feedback).  Feedback propagates back to trainers and institutional leads, not only upward to funders.  The governance structure adapts to carry a monitoring chain the current structure cannot.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT Reflexive Monitoring: 4.2 Communal Appraisal is the shared mechanism for judging whether a practice is working.  Without it, improvements are private and the programme cannot learn at the level that matters — aggregate effect across institutions.  The evaluation workstream is not an evaluation chain; building the workstream without building the chain is funded ambition without architecture.

    Ostrom's monitoring problem: Monitoring and information flows across action arenas determine whether the programme can learn and adjust.  When the chain has more links than the current governance can span, two options exist — shorten the chain (reduce scope) or restructure the governance (add actors and redistribute responsibilities).  Cross-institutional peer evaluation is a restructure: it distributes monitoring across the trainers themselves, converting them from producers of impression-based signals into a reciprocal evaluation network.

    Very-high coordination: This is the highest-coordination pattern (6+ actor chain).  Resolving it requires trainers at multiple institutions + a lightweight instrument + consent and data-sharing governance + an analyst who can see across + a feedback loop back to trainers and leads.  The paper is explicit that this is the hardest of the five.

    Convergent signal: This is the only pattern where COM-B quantitative data and qualitative transcript analysis produce the same conclusion independently — giving the claim more evidential weight than the other four.  The design move (lightweight cross-institutional instrument) is correspondingly specific.

    Learning-loop completion: Patterns 3 and 4 propagate local learning into materials and governance respectively.  Pattern 5 is the completion of the loop — aggregate outcomes propagating back into design, so the programme can judge whether the preceding four patterns are actually producing what they are meant to produce.  Without Pattern 5, the evidence that the other four are working stays anecdotal.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Design the evaluation chain end-to-end before the next delivery cycle, not as a retrofit
    - Assign named roles at each link: instrument designer, collector, cross-institutional analyst, feedback reporter
    - Develop and deploy a lightweight cross-institutional peer evaluation instrument (trainers interview each other's recipients)
    - Establish the consent and data-sharing governance the peer-evaluation design requires
    - Resource cross-institutional analysis explicitly — the central link, and the most absent
    - Design feedback to propagate back to trainers and institutional leads, not only upward to funders
    - Test: can the programme produce one cross-institutional learning report within its first year?
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    The programme maintains a complete evaluation chain from instrument design through cross-institutional analysis to feedback, with a named actor at each link and explicit resourcing for the cross-institutional analysis step.  Feedback propagates to trainers and institutional leads.  A cross-institutional peer evaluation mechanism is active.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Broken chain: instruments exist but no one analyses across institutions
    - Upward-only feedback: results reach funders but not trainers or institutional leads
    - Thin feedback: optional surveys yield only positive or absent responses
    - Workstream without chain: evaluation is funded on paper but the handoff chain is not built
    - Monitoring-chain overload: the chain has more links than the current governance can carry; the pattern fails because the structure was never adapted
    - Motivation erosion: trainers cannot see whether their effort matters beyond anecdote
    - Absent cross-institutional analysis: 4/4 ORP transcripts show this missing
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 5: Visible Impact
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B ("I have no other ways of getting feedback short of people filling in the feedback form")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B ("As we get like a few answers and nobody says this was terrible, I generally think it's gone quite well")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B (informal engagement signals)
    - Focus-group codes: FG2B.41, FG2B.36, FG2B.39 (informal signals from colleagues)
    - COM-B: "effects are being measured" M=3.35 (lowest item; dropped to 3.17 at 6-month follow-up)
    - Ostrom (1990) — monitoring problem, information flows across action arenas
    - Corneli (2016); Gervás & León (2014) — embedding evaluation in a learning loop
    - REDF proposal: Workstream 2 planned NPT-aligned surveys, case studies, ORCID tracking, dashboards
    - Role codebook: EV_analyse absent across 4/4 transcripts
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Reflexive Monitoring 4.2 Communal Appraisal as stated in the companion journal article.
    Tier: Architecture.  Coordination: Very high (multi-actor evaluation chain, the highest of the five).
    Implementation-mode link: this pattern's failure bounds multiplied input at network scale; its resolution closes the learning loop.
    The paper is explicit that this is the *only* pattern with a convergent COM-B + qualitative signal, and is the most consistently absent under current governance.
    The paper's resolution (cross-institutional peer evaluation via lightweight instrument) corresponds exactly to the working paper's Step 3 in the bootstrap sequence.
